00:25:21,946 --> 00:25:23,886
Black Panther is
taking on the Klan.


522
00:25:25,306 --> 00:25:29,306
He's actually ripping himself
off a cross before they set it


523
00:25:29,306 --> 00:25:30,226
on fire.


524
00:25:30,756 --> 00:25:36,286
What an emotional,
powerful, symbolic image.


525
00:25:36,616 --> 00:25:39,856
One of the things I love about
him is that he's outnumbered.


526
00:25:40,456 --> 00:25:43,176
I love that they chose, not
to just have one Klan member


527
00:25:43,176 --> 00:25:44,966
at the bottom, but there's
a whole group of them.


528
00:25:45,596 --> 00:25:47,966
This always -- this again
speaks to the Marvel message


529
00:25:47,966 --> 00:25:50,766
of underdogs feeling
outnumbered,


530
00:25:50,896 --> 00:25:54,616
feeling the world is against
you, but deciding to fight back,


531
00:25:54,616 --> 00:25:57,766
deciding to do the
right thing anyway.


532
00:25:58,636 --> 00:26:04,236
My next friend, she
was an orphan too.


533
00:26:04,236 --> 00:26:06,186
I think I should stop
there and talk about;


534
00:26:06,446 --> 00:26:10,626
what's up with all the orphans?


535
00:26:10,726 --> 00:26:14,256
Well, in any sort of art form
you have to make decisions to --


536
00:26:14,926 --> 00:26:16,936
especially in fiction --
you want to get the audience


537
00:26:17,136 --> 00:26:20,086
on the side of your character,
and if you have limited time,


538
00:26:20,156 --> 00:26:24,206
say a limited page count of a
comic book or a limited time


539
00:26:24,246 --> 00:26:26,016
in a movie or in a video game,


540
00:26:26,016 --> 00:26:27,776
you have to make
choices right away


541
00:26:27,776 --> 00:26:30,636
that helps your audience
connect with your character.


542
00:26:30,636 --> 00:26:33,386
So, that's why you -- it's a
tradition in heroic fiction,


543
00:26:33,686 --> 00:26:38,006
all these orphans; Luke
Skywalker, Harry Potter,


544
00:26:38,866 --> 00:26:43,486
every Disney princess,
poor Bambi.


545
00:26:43,486 --> 00:26:48,696
There goes mama [laughter]
Why do we do this?


546
00:26:49,856 --> 00:26:50,906
Why do we do this?


547
00:26:50,906 --> 00:26:52,746
Because again, we're
trying to get the audience


548
00:26:52,746 --> 00:26:53,866
on the side of the hero.


549
00:26:53,866 --> 00:26:57,226
And what's the one thing that
everyone can either fear,


550
00:26:58,306 --> 00:27:00,466
or if it's unfortunate enough
to have gone through it,


551
00:27:00,466 --> 00:27:03,126
to sympathize with,
losing the parents,


552
00:27:03,706 --> 00:27:05,076
something everyone can fear.


553
00:27:05,476 --> 00:27:07,226
So, it gets your audience
on the side of the hero.


554
00:27:07,226 --> 00:27:09,996
It also literally forces the
character out of the nest.


555
00:27:10,296 --> 00:27:13,256
Our characters must now
stand on their own two feet


556
00:27:13,256 --> 00:27:16,236
and again make their choices
about power and responsibility.


557
00:27:16,236 --> 00:27:19,946
So, that's why you often see
it in super heroes like this.


558
00:27:19,946 --> 00:27:22,846
So, my next friend;
she was an orphan


559
00:27:23,106 --> 00:27:24,316
and she felt like a freak.


